,-0.036088138818740845,-0.03544880449771881,0.025238556787371635,0.046392057090997696,-0.029323691502213478,-0.01563337817788124,-0.07506796717643738,-0.01054334081709385,0.005930016282945871,0.04011064022779465,0.014391650445759296,-0.06397256255149841,-0.02423708327114582,-0.01907389797270298,-0.039015091955661774,0.023982778191566467,-0.05907575041055679,-0.06397737562656403,-0.016675621271133423,0.022614624351263046,0.057788021862506866,-0.005245326552540064,0.10333258658647537,-0.0478227436542511],"file_id":"422e5c03-d3a1-4f02-8666-0cf70930a235"},{"chunk":{"content":"**Aim 1: Developing BM TME models with holistic, multimodal AI-driven\nanalysis.** We will rely on orthotopic immunocompetent murine models for\nmelanoma BMs developed by the Weiss group together with the large cohort\nof patient clinical samples collected by the Weiss group and our\ncollaborators in hospitals in Israel. These will be used to create\nsingle-cell atlases of immune, stromal and tumor cells from human and\nmurine BMs. We will go significantly beyond the state of the art, by\nbuilding integrated tissue models from single cells and holistically\ninferring their physiology and potential drug response. We will use\nnovel technology developed in our groups for cell temporal tracking\n(ZMAN-seq, differentiation flows), cell-cell interactions (PIC-seq), and\nimproved strategies for AI analysis of spatial transcriptomics with\nStereo-seq. Our tools will identify shared processes and pathways\nbetween our models and human patient TMEs, enabling us to compile a list\nof cytokines with potentially high antitumor activity in melanoma BMs.","content_hash":"ebd56d4c88705ab8a49d95feabe5b34d64e884948c4e201b02c3cd95ede8f0a6","index":1,"element_type":"raw"},"embedding":[-0.03827066719532013,-0.01288565993309021,0.03454124927520752,-0.03318009525537491,-0.012478797696530819,0.00836343877017498,-0.07017447054386139,0.03786955028772354,0.04245341196656227,0.022116050124168396,-0.029333043843507767,-0.0446